    <section>
      <div class="card">
     <center>  <img src="n4.jpg" alt="portrait1"></center> 
        <div class="content">
          <h2 style="color: blue ; text-decoration: underline;">A more agile IS:</h2>
          
          <center>  <p1>In the cloud, the end user of the service can quickly provision the
            resources it needs (servers, networks, storage, applications, etc.) and dispose of it without
            having to go through long and complex manual configuration steps. Those
            "rapid provisioning" and "self-service" capabilities enable the IS to respond
            more quickly to the needs of the trades, to the requests for changes, as well as to the requirements
            increasing time-to-market. In some consumption models, this agility is
            taken to the extreme, particularly in SaaS or PaaS type models or the company
            frees itself from a large number of constraints in setting up its applications.
            
            
          </p1></center>
          
        </div>
     
      </div>
  
      <div class="card">
      <center> <img src="n5.jpg" alt="portrait2"></center> 
        <div class="content">
          <h2 style="color: blue ; text-decoration: underline;">Usage-based billing:</h2>
         
          <center>    <p1>With the Cloud, a new usage-based billing method is becoming widespread, which can be summarized
            simply: you only pay for what you actually consume. In the Cloud
            of infrastructure, we thus pay for the number of processor cores consumed, the quantity
            of memory used, the number of input/output operations performed or the quantity
            of stored data. In a SaaS mode, you pay by the number of users and according to
            their use of resources.
            
            
          </p1></center> 
         
        </div>
      </div>
  
     
